    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "And FWIW:\r\n\r\n[`make`](https://savannah.gnu.org/bugs/?18396) installs `RLIMIT_STACK` to `RLIM64_INFINITY` and because of this new threads will be created with default limit (2mb for `x86_64`, according to `pthread_create`(2)) instead of inheriting limit from the parent (which will be 8mb), and since after this [patch](https://lkml.org/lkml/2017/11/1/1040) linux limits length for argv to 25% of the stack (min), we have only 128K for the length of argv, which is not enough for that `install` target (on my machine it requires ~133KB)\r\n\r\nPlus there is `MAX_ARG_STRLEN`, that said that length of one argument cannot be greater then 128KiB, and since this will be wrapped to a single argument (`sh -c \"...\"`) it will also fail, regardless current stack limit."
  },
